STYLE & FASHION

BY CHARLIE TEASDALE

LIKE walking down the street with a watch that may not look special, but it is special—it has that age and originality to it,” said

Jeffrey Binstock, 62, a watch lover

and former media exec in New

York. Some of Binstock's most be-

loved models are decades-old and,

if you look closely, show their age.

“Scratches, dents, ‘crazed [visibly

cracked] dials—that doesn't bother

me at all,” said Binstock.

Among his favorites: an elegant 1950s Longines with a lightly scuffed steel case and once-lumi- nous hands that have faded to yel- lowish green; a "70s chronograph with a subtly cracked bezel. See- ing the effects of an old watch’s “natural evolution” appeals to Bin- stock. Attempts at restoration— polishing the case, replacing the dial—can be like destroying the water's soul, he said.

For an in-the-know subset of watch lovers, worn-in character beats pristine perfection. These guys find charmingly beat-up watches cooler and more stylish, like a favorite faded pair of Levi's. And they often cost less than new or immaculate vintage models.

Christopher Bastin, 50, the Swedish creative director of fash- fon brand Gant, wears a scratched- but-handsome Rolex Submariner from the 70s. “The dial flew off while I was working in the garden

“Scratches, dents, cracked dials—they don’t bother me at all?

last year,” he said. “To me, having a watch that you need to be care- ful and all prissy about is point- less.” London stylist Julian Ganio often uses old watches in shoots— he appreciates the “reality” they bring to a look. And the 43-year- old values his own yellow-gold Rolex Day-Date for its scruffy con- dition. “1 like that it's of a certain age and well-worn—just like me and my style.”

Beyond tossing your Rolex in the washer-dryer and hoping for the best, how can you nab an agreeably patinated timepiece— and what should you look for?

First off, you want a watch that works, not a broken wreck, says Dy- lan Lewis, founder of Goldfinger's Vintage in Brooklyn. Scratches, sub- tle dents or discoloration can sup-

ply the desired look, but cracked glass can compromise a watchs in- tegrity (for instance, by letting moisture inside). A misshapen dial or hand, meanwhile, can affect the movement or make it hard to tell the time. Avoid watches with loose parts—if they rattle, run.

Buy from a trusted source, says Eric Wind, a vintage dealer in Palm Beach, Fla. Wind recounts horror stories of “Frankenstein” watches he has seen that are stitched together from disparate parts. “You really need to know who you're buying it from...It's a tricky field,” he said. You could “overpay grotesquely,” he added.

Watchfinder.com, the site owned by luxury group Richemont, is a go-to source for vintage watches, but if you want a noticeably worn

model, best track down a reliable dealer, such as Wind, Lewis or Da- vid Silver, owner of the Vintage Watch Company in London.

You might score a great deal. In general, a pristine vintage watch will cost more than one in poor

Lewis recently sold an un- polished '80s Cartier Santos with a subtly scratched steel case for $4,350. If it had been in mint con- dition, it could have gone for $5,000 or $6,000, he says. Aaron Faber Gallery, a New York store, sells appealingly aged designs from around $1300 up to $7,000-plus. In the case of so-called “tropical” dials, damage can send the value soaring, says Silver. These rare di- als, found on mideentury models

with faulty lacquering, have changed color after extended exposure to di- rect light or humidity. A once-black dial might now be hazy purple or deep brown and flecked with curi- ous spots and striations. In the watch world, “‘unique’ gets thrashed around a lot,” said Silver, “but tropi- cal dials [really] are unique.”

Binstock, the former exec, con- siders wearing a beautifully blem- ished ticker—whether one with a discolored dial or a scuffed case— a private luxury. Only he’s aware of its quirks, he said, adding that it doesn't “scream on the wrist.”
